ow Coinbase describes the refund:success event:This event is sent when a refund has completed and can no longer be changed.You can use the refund:success event to update your records or trigger an action in your system when a refund is issued. For example, you could use this event to update an order status or send a notification to the customer.For more information on the refund:success event and other events that can be tracked using Coinbase webhooks, you can refer to the Coinbase API documentation.How can i find out if a charge was unsucessfulThere are a few ways you can determine if a charge was unsuccessful:Use the charge:resolved event: As I mentioned earlier, the charge:resolved event is sent by Coinbase when a charge is either successful or fails. You can use this event to determine the outcome of the charge. In the event data, the status field will be set to success if the charge was successful, or failed if the charge was unsuccessful.Check the charge status: You can also check the status of a charge using the Coinbase API. To do this, you can use the GET /v2/charges/{charge_id} endpoint, which returns detailed information about a specific charge, including its status. The status will be set to completed if the charge was successful, or failed if the charge was unsuccessful.Monitor your webhook logs: If you have set up Coinbase webhooks, you can also monitor your webhook logs to see which events have been sent. If a charge was unsuccessful, you should see a charge:resolved event with a status of failed.I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.

